<BlogPost
  title="Feeds for Machines: RSS as the Structured Layer for AI"
  description="LLMs are starving for clean, structured, permissioned content. A 25-year-old syndication format turns out to be a surprisingly good answer."
  slug="rss-and-ai"
  tag="AI"
  date="2026-06-16"
>
  <p>
    Most of what an AI system reads about the world, it reads by scraping HTML, fighting through nav bars,
    cookie banners, ad slots, and markup that was written for a browser, not a model. It works, badly. There
    is a cleaner path that has been sitting in plain sight: the feed.
  </p>

  <h2>What a feed gives a model</h2>
  <p>An RSS or Atom feed is content with the chrome already removed:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Structure</strong>: title, author, timestamp, and body in labeled fields, not guessed at from
      <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> soup.</li>
    <li><strong>Freshness</strong>: feeds are ordered and timestamped, so &ldquo;what changed since I last
      looked&rdquo; is a trivial question instead of a re-crawl.</li>
    <li><strong>Intent</strong>: a publisher who offers a feed is explicitly saying &ldquo;here is my content,
      meant to be consumed by software.&rdquo; That&rsquo;s a permission signal scraping never has.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The permission problem</h2>
  <p>
    The tension between AI crawlers and publishers is, at bottom, about consent and structure. Scraping takes
    without asking and guesses at meaning. A feed is the opposite: a publisher deciding what to syndicate, in a
    format that says what each part <em>is</em>. As the relationship between models and the open web gets
    renegotiated, feeds are a natural unit, granular, opt-in, and machine-clean.
  </p>
  <blockquote>If you were designing &ldquo;structured, permissioned, time-ordered content for machines&rdquo; from scratch, you&rsquo;d land somewhere close to RSS.</blockquote>

  <h2>What feeds don&rsquo;t solve</h2>
  <p>
    Feeds aren&rsquo;t a silver bullet, and it&rsquo;s worth being honest about the gaps. Not every site offers
    one. Full-text feeds are rarer than they should be, plenty publish only a summary. And a feed still
    can&rsquo;t capture everything a rich, interactive page does. But as the default unit for &ldquo;give a
    model clean, recent, opt-in content,&rdquo; a feed beats scraping on every axis that matters: structure,
    freshness, cost, and consent. It puts the publisher back in charge of what gets shared.
  </p>

  <h2>Where this goes</h2>
  <p>
    The practical near-term version is unglamorous and useful: point a model at a set of feeds instead of a set
    of URLs to scrape, and let RSS-to-JSON do the parsing so the content arrives clean. Retrieval pipelines,
    monitoring agents, and &ldquo;summarize what&rsquo;s new&rdquo; tools all get simpler when the source already
    speaks a structured dialect.
  </p>
  <p>
    It&rsquo;s a nice irony. The format everyone wrote off a decade ago turns out to be well-suited to the most
    hyped technology of this one. KB Cafe is building its <a href="/feeds">feed tools</a> with that in mind, and
    an <a href="/#menu">AI-tools</a> corner alongside them.
  </p>

